Crossposted-To: comp.windows.x.i386unix
From: andreas@fly.mgen.uni-heidelberg.de (Andreas Helke)
Subject: Re: SVGA Card Recommendations?
Date: Mon, 27 Sep 1993 12:16:53 GMT

In article <CDy7Cq.1r74@ns1.nodak.edu> bakke@plains.NoDak.edu (Jeffrey P. Bakke) writes:


>I'm trying to decide on a video board to purchase for use on my new 
>486DX-50 machine that I recently purchased.  I'm looking for the best
>recommendation that someone can give me for an ISA(uggh) SVGA video

ISA is not too bad for most video applications. For most standard programs, 
wordprocessing, spreadsheets etc. you get between 0 and 15% improvement with a 
local bus card, depending on the speed of your CPU.

>board.   I'm not heavy into windows so, S3 doesn't thrill me.  I'm 
>looking for board in the $100-$250 range that gives me good DOS-based
>performance (ie, running Flight simulator 5.0) and good X11 performance
>under XFree running Linux.  From what I've seen and read I know that I'm
>limited in my choices for XFree and as far as I can tell, the ET-4000/w32
>chipset seems to be a preferred.  So the question stands, if you were to
>buy and ISA SVGA card for XFree (mainly) what would you go with?   Along
>the same lines, I do have a cheapo Trident 8900C that works, what type of
>performance increase would I see using the ET-4000 based card?  Finally,
>since ET-4000 seems to be very popular, what SVGA cards use this chipset?
>Does the Diamond series?  I can get a good price on aiamond SpeedStar
>24X card.  Will it work with Xfree and is it a good deal or would you 
>recommend something else?

X gets a tremendous performance boost if you use the accelerated features of 
an appropriate chipset. I at present use a 486/33 8 MB with the old Ati 
graphics ultra. This works much faster when I use the 8514a part with the 
x8514scale server than with the Ati VGA part with the normal svga server. 

The combination of inexpensive, and as well good DOS as good X performance is 
at present problematic. At present, only S3 and 8514a chipsets are supported 
as accelerated chipsets. If price does not matter, a Ati graphics ultra pro is 
probably your best choice. With the soon to be released Xfree version 2 a card 
with the Cirrus GD5426 or 5428 chipset is probably a good idea, if the 
card should be inexpensive. (I intend to buy one, for another computer on 
which I want to install linux, as soon as I get the necessary harddisk 
space. I only do not know, wich model works best or at all. Spea V7 Vega or 
Genoa 8500 come to my mind. But I will probably wait until I get information 
that one of those or another card actually works with Xfree. ) The Tseng 
ET4000/W32 is good as DOS VGA card, but unfortunately not supported as 
accelerated card by the Xfree server. (It works only as a normal ET4000.)

Buying a Diamod card will give you extra headaches, because Diamod keeps 
important technical information secret. This prevents Diamod cards from beeing 
supported by Xfree.

Andreas
-
Andreas Helke, Molekulare Genetik, Universitaet Heidelberg, Germany
email un69ef@genius.embnet.dkfz-heidelberg.de
      andreas@fly.mgen.uni-heidelberg.de 

